The goal of this experiment was to see how different physical properties affect the oscillation period of a torsional pendulum, and to check of the results agree with theory. We found that the release angle does not change the period as long as the angle is small, which is what the theory predicts. The period increased when used a longer rod or a longer wire, and increased slightly when we added more mass to the rod. A thicker wire made the period shorter, because the wire became stiffer.

The logarithmic graphs showed clear linear trends, which means the relationships can be described with power laws as expected. Overall, the results match the theoretical model well. Some small errors probably came from manual timing and small differences in how the pendulum was set in motion each time. Despite that, the experiment clearly confirmed the expected behavior of torsional oscillations. 

By changing one parameter at a time and comparing the results from each test series, we could clearly see how each physical quantity affected the oscillation period. The experiment therefore gave a practical understanding of torsional motion and showed that the chosen method was useful for studying these relationships under simple laboratory conditions.